  "final_answer": "Yes. There are several cases where median income is very similar but median house value is very different.\n\nExamples:\n- In the income range 2.546 to 3.031:\n  - INLAND: median income 2.754, median house value $98,100\n  - ISLAND: median income 2.833, median house value $414,700\n  - Difference: $316,600\n\n- In the same income range:\n  - <1H OCEAN: median income 2.773, median house value $170,400\n  - ISLAND: median income 2.833, median house value $414,700\n  - Difference: $244,300\n\n- Also in that range:\n  - ISLAND: median income 2.833, median house value $414,700\n  - NEAR BAY: median income 2.796, median house value $183,800\n  - Difference: $230,900\n\n- In the income range 4.043 to 4.743:\n  - INLAND: median income 4.294, median house value $143,100\n  - NEAR OCEAN: median income 4.317, median house value $271,000\n  - Difference: $127,900\n\n- In the income range 4.743 to 5.832:\n  - INLAND: median income 5.191, median house value $174,800\n  - NEAR OCEAN: median income 5.181, median house value $299,700\n  - Difference: $124,900\n\nWhat likely explains the differences:\n- Ocean proximity: Coastal, bay-adjacent, and island locations command a premium even when incomes are similar.\n- Scarcity of land: Waterfront and island housing is more limited, which pushes prices up.\n- Desirability and amenities: Views, beach access, climate, and neighborhood appeal increase values.\n- Access to jobs and services: Some coastal and bay areas may be closer to employment centers and amenities.\n- Housing characteristics: Higher-value areas often also have older housing stock, which may reflect more established and desirable neighborhoods.\n- Local market effects: Demand, zoning, and neighborhood reputation can raise prices independently of resident income.\n\nImportant note:\n- The ISLAND category has only 1 record, so those comparisons are striking but should be treated cautiously.\n- Overall, the clearest pattern is that coastal and bay-adjacent areas tend to have much higher house values than inland areas at similar income levels.",
